step.context:
\text{If $A\times B=C$ where A B and C are matrices }\\
\text{and A and B are of orders $m\times n$ and $p\times q$}\\
\text{respectively, are the following always true?}

\left[\begin{array}{cc}
 a & b \\ 
 c & d \end{array} \right]\times
\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
 1 & 2 & 3 \\ 
 4 & 5 & 6 \end{array} \right]=C\\
 \text{Is this correct?}

step.reason:
A_{m\times n}\times B_{n\times p}=C_{m\times p}\\
\text{where } C = [c_{ik}]\text{ and }
c_{ik}=\sum_{j=1}^{n} a_{ij}\cdot b_{jk}

step.context:
\text{If } \left[\begin{array}{ccc}
 a+4b & 2a+5b & 3a+6b \\ 
 c+4d & 2c+5d & 3c+6d \end{array} \right]=
\left[\text{}^{-7}_{\,\,\,\, 2} \text{ }^{-8}_{\,\,\,\, 4} \text{ }^{-9}_{\,\,\,\, 6}\right]\\
\text{ then the following must be true:}

step.reason:
A=B \implies \text{ A and B are two matrices of the}\\
\text{same order and $a_{ij} = b_{ij}$, where $n_{ij}$ is element}\\
\text{at the $i^{th}$ row and $j^{th}$ column.}

\text{The equations represent three distinct lines}\\
\text{which happen to coincide. Solving for a and b}\\
\text{using any two would give the same result.}

